english:
  title: Record of the New Pavilion at Yongin
  author: Kim Su-ryeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yongin is but a small county, yet because it lies adjacent to the royal capital, travelers great and small flow through it day and night without cease—truly the throat connecting north and south. The old inn was cramped, barely fit for a single night's rest. When summer heat descended, it became stuffy and oppressive, leaving guests no refuge for their weary hearts. They would suffer from the scorching heat and endless troubles, a malady long endured.

    In the winter of the fourth year of Chun-sun, Governor Park arrived to oversee this county. With generous taxation and swift administration, he swept away all manner of ills. Officials trembled in respect, and the people held him dear. One day, the Governor consulted with his officials: "I wish to gather materials and construct a pavilion—a place where guests might escape the summer heat. Do you think it wise?" Since they already recognized his virtuous governance, all responded: "We shall gladly exhaust our efforts."

    Therefore the craftsmen became diligent, the laborers industrious. Working through dawn and dusk, they completed the work within a month. At first, the people knew nothing of the pavilion being built. Once finished, beholding it they marveled: "Does our Governor possess that ancient virtue called divine wisdom? How is it the pavilion appeared without our knowledge?" Together they gazed upon it in wonder and celebration of this new creation.

    Yet when I observe the magistrates of this world today, they drowse in wine-soaked dreams, treating the official residence as a mere inn—waiting until the roof caves before mending the beams, until rain leaks before plugging the holes. The worst among them will not replace a single tile, yet claim: "I cherish my people." They will not pull a single weed, yet declare: "There is no litigation in my court." The decay of government halls springs eternally from such men. How many can be found who strive with purpose from the beginning? How few achieve such work while remaining unknown to their people!

    Once, traveling southward by imperial summons, I passed through Yongin. Governor Park presented me with brush and ink, requesting that I write this record. After I had set down my humble words, he said: "The pavilion has received a record—fortunate indeed. Yet it lacks a name. What shall we do?" I replied: "A name is proper, certainly. Yet the absence of a name is not necessarily a flaw. Without a Governor like yourself in Yongin, this pavilion could never have been built. Had it not been built, how could a name ever exist? To give it a name through its namelessness is itself a good name, is it not?"

    He pressed me further to take more care. Gathering the spirit of the people's wonder and celebration of this new creation, I suggested we call it the New Pavilion. Does not the saying tell us: "That which is called new has an origin in what is old"? Thus too lies a gentlemen's deeper meaning. Governor Park's name is Geo-myeong, his courtesy name is Hoe-bo, and he is of the Milyang clan.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'New Pavilion' (新亭) represents both a literal structure and a metaphor for good governance—the pavilion exists because of the Governor's virtuous administration, making it an expression of his character rather than merely a building.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Divine wisdom'' (神明) is a Confucian concept referring to enlightened and virtuous leadership that operates almost effortlessly, accomplishing great works while appearing to do nothing.'
